Division of Heme at Ohio State University's

27
00:01:23.680 --> 00:01:27.320
Comprehensive Cancer Center, and she's going to be looking a little bit

28
00:01:27.400 --> 00:01:31.260
about some of these things with respect to CLL and

29
00:01:31.340 --> 00:01:35.000
BTK inhibitors. So, without further ado, I'm going

30
00:01:35.020 --> 00:01:36.920
to pass on to

31
00:01:37.740 --> 00:01:41.140
our first speaker, which is Dr. Pickman. So, thank you, Dr. Pickman.

32
00:01:51.360 --> 00:01:52.060
Good afternoon.

33
00:01:53.580 --> 00:01:54.280
Yes, good afternoon.

34
00:01:56.500 --> 00:02:00.220
I really would like to thank the organizers for the invitation to talk to you

35
00:02:00.320 --> 00:02:01.800
today about some

36
00:02:02.680 --> 00:02:06.400
functional genomic and drug screening approaches for precision medicine

37
00:02:07.020 --> 00:02:10.320
in acute leukemia. As Dr. Davis said, I'm a pediatric

38
00:02:10.380 --> 00:02:11.660
oncologist, so

39
00:02:13.040 --> 00:02:16.860
I will focus on pediatric acute leukemias during my

40
00:02:16.920 --> 00:02:17.240
talk.

41
00:02:19.640 --> 00:02:23.320
Pediatric cancer has a very low mutation burden, as you can

42
00:02:23.440 --> 00:02:27.200
see here, and this also applies to acute

43
00:02:27.240 --> 00:02:28.340
leukemias in

44
00:02:29.280 --> 00:02:31.160
pediatrics.

45
00:02:32.020 --> 00:02:35.980
And so when we talk about precision medicine efforts and this idea of trying to

46
00:02:36.060 --> 00:02:39.480
match therapy to the genomic

47
00:02:39.600 --> 00:02:43.480
alteration that a particular tumor has, that becomes

48
00:02:43.520 --> 00:02:46.860
very difficult when there are actually few mutations.

49
00:02:48.140 --> 00:02:50.180
When we look at the targets that are

50
00:02:51.520 --> 00:02:55.500
found in pediatric acute leukemias in T-cell

51
00:02:55.580 --> 00:02:58.940
ALL, B-cell ALL, and acute myeloid leukemia,

52
00:02:59.640 --> 00:03:03.200
these targets are often transcription factors, epigenetic

53
00:03:03.280 --> 00:03:05.540
targets, or other targets that are

54
00:03:06.360 --> 00:03:08.500
traditionally thought to be undruggable.

55
00:03:09.100 --> 00:03:10.660
So, what do we do with that?

56
00:03:12.600 --> 00:03:14.780
And I'll show you one example here.

57
00:03:14.940 --> 00:03:15.320
This is

58
00:03:16.680 --> 00:03:20.580
in the pediatric acute myeloid leukemia where the

59
00:03:21.380 --> 00:03:22.880
disease is often

60
00:03:24.240 --> 00:03:27.880
driven by somatic fusions that occur,

61
00:03:28.300 --> 00:03:32.200
and with, again, relatively few other mutations that are

62
00:03:32.240 --> 00:03:35.940
present. And you can see from the names of some of these subgroups,

63
00:03:36.200 --> 00:03:39.940
these are often transcription factors, and again, are difficult to

64
00:03:39.980 --> 00:03:40.320
drug.

65
00:03:41.340 --> 00:03:45.280
But there have been a number of efforts that have shown

66
00:03:45.340 --> 00:03:47.740
that if you can identify the

67
00:03:47.760 --> 00:03:51.380
targetable alteration, and especially if it's a

68
00:03:51.420 --> 00:03:55.000
fusion, this can really make a significant impact in

69
00:03:55.700 --> 00:03:56.980
treatment of the disease.

70
00:03:57.850 --> 00:04:00.860
And in acute myeloid leukemia, these fusions

71
00:04:00.960 --> 00:04:04.600
define subtypes that are specific and

72
00:04:04.740 --> 00:04:07.960
associated with their distinct risk

73
00:04:08.340 --> 00:04:12.170
prognosis, and we alter therapy based on

74
00:04:12.200 --> 00:04:15.870
the fusions that appear. But again, some of these alterations

75
00:04:17.019 --> 00:04:17.481
are such,

76
00:04:18.409 --> 00:04:22.140
like introduction of stem cell transplant, so not really

77
00:04:22.200 --> 00:04:23.840
targeted therapies per se.

78
00:04:25.540 --> 00:04:27.360
So today, I'll talk about

79
00:04:28.300 --> 00:04:32.240
three potential ways that we can think about drugging the

80
00:04:32.260 --> 00:04:36.240
undruggable. The first is using functional genomic screening

81
00:04:36.680 --> 00:04:39.900
to identify dependencies in particular

82
00:04:39.940 --> 00:04:40.700
leukemias

83
00:04:41.560 --> 00:04:43.320
or other cancers for that matter.

84
00:04:44.640 --> 00:04:47.580
The second is to think about surface target

85
00:04:47.680 --> 00:04:51.140
identification in cancers. And the third,

86
00:04:51.680 --> 00:04:55.600
drug sensitivity screening that can be done on primary patient samples

87
00:04:55.680 --> 00:04:58.860
and becomes agnostic to the type of mutations that are present.

88
00:05:02.940 --> 00:05:05.320
One way that I think

89
00:05:06.120 --> 00:05:09.910
functional genomic screening has been really transformed

90
00:05:10.120 --> 00:05:13.290
and has made these

91
00:05:14.420 --> 00:05:18.380
methodologies available to people everywhere has been

92
00:05:18.420 --> 00:05:20.880
through the development of the Cancer Dependency Map.

93
00:05:21.880 --> 00:05:25.640
This effort from the Broad Institute, led by a

94
00:05:25.700 --> 00:05:28.600
number of very talented scientists,

95
00:05:29.640 --> 00:05:32.740
has over the last eight years, collected

96
00:05:33.700 --> 00:05:37.180
over 2,000 models, cancer cell lines and other cancer

97
00:05:37.220 --> 00:05:41.100
models. These models are profiled using a

98
00:05:41.140 --> 00:05:42.460
number of various omic

99
00:05:43.500 --> 00:05:43.960
efforts,

100
00:05:45.320 --> 00:05:46.880
both genetic and epigenetic

101
00:05:48.440 --> 00:05:51.860
profiling, and are subject to genetic and

102
00:05:51.900 --> 00:05:53.400
chemical perturbations.

103
00:05:54.520 --> 00:05:58.380
When this data is combined, the omic profiling with the

104
00:05:58.700 --> 00:06:02.620
genetic and chemical perturbations and analyzed, this can lead

105
00:06:02.680 --> 00:06:05.200
to a number of therapeutic hypotheses that can then be

106
00:06:05.260 --> 00:06:08.788
tested.Over the last several years,

107
00:06:09.268 --> 00:06:13.028
efforts led by Doctors Kim Stadlinger, Charlie Roberts, and

108
00:06:13.068 --> 00:06:16.707
Paquita Vazquez has also expanded DepMap to

109
00:06:16.768 --> 00:06:20.668
include additional pediatric models in the effort called PedDep.

110
00:06:22.628 --> 00:06:26.528
So my first example actually has to do with T-cell acute lymphoblastic

111
00:06:26.568 --> 00:06:30.548
leukemia. This is a very heterogeneous disease, and work from

112
00:06:30.588 --> 00:06:34.208
Charles Mullighan's group has defined over 17 different

113
00:06:34.268 --> 00:06:37.908
subtypes of T-ALL, each associated with its own prognosis.

114
00:06:38.028 --> 00:06:40.648
And again, you can see some of the names of the transcription factors

115
00:06:40.708 --> 00:06:44.428
here. We used the dependency map

116
00:06:44.728 --> 00:06:46.308
to ask whether there are specific

117
00:06:47.168 --> 00:06:50.648
dependencies that are present in T-ALL over other

118
00:06:50.708 --> 00:06:54.498
cancers and found that one-carbon folate pathway,

119
00:06:54.848 --> 00:06:58.108
as well as purine and pyrimidine metabolism, were particular

120
00:06:58.188 --> 00:07:02.108
dependencies in T-ALL versus other cancers and other

121
00:07:02.128 --> 00:07:03.768
hematologic malignancies.

122
00:07:04.838 --> 00:07:08.648
This is a very simplified schematic of the one-carbon folate pathway,

123
00:07:09.728 --> 00:07:13.508
which contributes significantly

124
00:07:13.568 --> 00:07:14.848
to lipid metabolism,

125
00:07:15.748 --> 00:07:18.248
methylation, production of purines and pyrimidines.

126
00:07:18.888 --> 00:07:22.688
And you can see these enzymes, SHMT1 and SHMT2, which

127
00:07:23.488 --> 00:07:25.128
can be inhibited by various drugs.

128
00:07:25.298 --> 00:07:27.808
And we worked with a drug called

129
00:07:28.008 --> 00:07:31.288
RZ2994 that was developed by Raize

130
00:07:31.428 --> 00:07:32.148
Therapeutics.

131
00:07:33.468 --> 00:07:37.348
When we looked in target T-ALL data, you can see that a

132
00:07:37.388 --> 00:07:41.048
subset of T-ALLs, these are enriched in the

133
00:07:41.148 --> 00:07:44.798
MKX2.1 subtype, had increased

134
00:07:44.848 --> 00:07:48.798
expression of the one-carbon folate pathway, purine and

135
00:07:48.808 --> 00:07:50.048
pyrimidine metabolism.

136
00:07:51.708 --> 00:07:55.368
And then, of course, we needed to validate the SHMT1 and

137
00:07:55.468 --> 00:07:58.248
2 as a target at a lower throughput.

138
00:07:59.108 --> 00:08:02.338
Using CRISPR knockout, we found that in T-ALL,

139
00:08:02.928 --> 00:08:06.708
loss of SHMT1 and 2 both were needed to

140
00:08:07.568 --> 00:08:10.208
decrease cell growth and lead to cell death.

141
00:08:11.248 --> 00:08:15.228
And in the mouse model of T-ALL, treatment using

142
00:08:15.368 --> 00:08:18.008
the RZ2994 compound

143
00:08:18.868 --> 00:08:21.568
also led to a decrease in

144
00:08:22.648 --> 00:08:25.428
T-ALL burden in the bone marrow and the spleen.

145
00:08:26.817 --> 00:08:30.638
So this is the way the functional genomic screening was able to identify

146
00:08:30.848 --> 00:08:34.718
a selective vulnerability in T-ALL, and we were

147
00:08:34.768 --> 00:08:38.518
able to validate SHMT1 and 2, members of the one-carbon folate

148
00:08:38.608 --> 00:08:42.268
pathway, as necessary to impair growth

149
00:08:42.688 --> 00:08:43.588
in T-ALL,

150
00:08:44.468 --> 00:08:48.178
and showed efficacy of inhibition of SHMT1 and 2 in

151
00:08:48.208 --> 00:08:49.108
T-ALL models.

152
00:08:50.948 --> 00:08:54.268
My next example will take us to acute myeloid leukemia

153
00:08:54.948 --> 00:08:58.668
and a particular subtype of acute myeloid leukemia that is

154
00:08:58.908 --> 00:09:00.928
really only present in young children

155
00:09:01.828 --> 00:09:03.268
that are less than four years of age.

156
00:09:04.068 --> 00:09:06.408
This is defined by this translocation in

157
00:09:06.448 --> 00:09:10.348
CBFA2-T3, GLIS2. So these are transcription

158
00:09:10.528 --> 00:09:14.458
factors. This type of leukemia is

159
00:09:14.468 --> 00:09:16.708
present in 20% of

160
00:09:17.908 --> 00:09:20.348
children with acute megakaryoblastic leukemia.

161
00:09:21.648 --> 00:09:25.408
These patients have few other mutations other than this

162
00:09:25.428 --> 00:09:29.388
translocation. And you can see have really quite poor outcomes.

163
00:09:32.008 --> 00:09:34.728
Work from Kim Stadlinger's group has

164
00:09:36.608 --> 00:09:40.168
used functional screening to identify targets for

165
00:09:40.248 --> 00:09:41.768
GLIS2 rearranged AML.

166
00:09:42.748 --> 00:09:46.668
So here, leukemia cell lines expressing Cas9 and

167
00:09:47.248 --> 00:09:51.228
characterized by this GLIS2 rearrangement were transduced

168
00:09:51.348 --> 00:09:55.008
with whole genome CRISPR libraries and

169
00:09:55.488 --> 00:09:58.908
passaged over three weeks and then sequenced.

170
00:09:59.968 --> 00:10:02.908
What they found in three of the models that had the GLIS2

171
00:10:02.948 --> 00:10:06.848
rearrangement was that these were dependent on

172
00:10:06.908 --> 00:10:10.888
the JAK2 kinase, non-receptor tyrosine kinase, as

173
00:10:10.928 --> 00:10:11.718
well as JAK1,

174
00:10:12.648 --> 00:10:15.668
a related kinase. And both can be

175
00:10:16.368 --> 00:10:20.268
inhibited by ruxolitinib, an inhibitor of JAK1 and 2.

176
00:10:20.308 --> 00:10:22.128
So this was particularly exciting.

177
00:10:23.007 --> 00:10:26.168
Again, they went on to validate this finding at low throughput.

178
00:10:26.968 --> 00:10:30.128
So this is one of the GLIS2 rearranged models where loss of

179
00:10:30.188 --> 00:10:33.408
JAK2 led to a decrease in leukemia cell

180
00:10:33.628 --> 00:10:37.568
growth. And then in vivo, similarly, loss of JAK2 led to a

181
00:10:37.668 --> 00:10:39.508
decrease in leukemia burden.

182
00:10:41.188 --> 00:10:44.948
When looking at the survival of the mice, you can

183
00:10:45.008 --> 00:10:47.968
see that loss of JAK2 led to some

184
00:10:47.988 --> 00:10:51.948
prolongation in survival of these mice, but certainly

185
00:10:52.008 --> 00:10:53.288
not cure.

186
00:10:54.228 --> 00:10:57.628
And perhaps most importantly, we had a patient who was

187
00:10:57.648 --> 00:10:58.448
treated,

188
00:10:59.368 --> 00:11:03.278
who had GLIS2 rearranged AML and was treated with ruxolitinib and had

189
00:11:03.568 --> 00:11:05.948
a response initially but then progressed.

190
00:11:06.968 --> 00:11:08.328
And so that

191
00:11:09.588 --> 00:11:09.968
really

192
00:11:11.928 --> 00:11:15.828
speaks to the need for target therapies and perhaps some inherent resistance

193
00:11:16.268 --> 00:11:18.268
to this type of approach.

194
00:11:20.088 --> 00:11:23.548
So they then turned to functional

195
00:11:23.648 --> 00:11:27.608
screening to try to address the mechanism of resistance

196
00:11:27.668 --> 00:11:28.628
in these leukemias.

197
00:11:29.848 --> 00:11:33.808
So here again are the AML cells with the GLIS2

198
00:11:33.868 --> 00:11:37.608
fusion that were transduced with a whole genome

199
00:11:37.628 --> 00:11:41.368
CRISPR library and then grown either with the

200
00:11:41.408 --> 00:11:45.108
JAK1-2 inhibitor ruxolitinib or without it to identify

201
00:11:45.118 --> 00:11:48.028
genes that are depleted or enriched in the setting of the drug.

202
00:11:49.748 --> 00:11:52.618
Identified here were a number of genes,

203
00:11:53.528 --> 00:11:57.428
and some were negative regulators of

204
00:11:57.488 --> 00:12:01.088
the MAPK signaling pathway, like RASA2, for example here.

205
00:12:02.388 --> 00:12:06.078
As I said, RASA2 is a negative regulator of the MAP kinase

206
00:12:06.168 --> 00:12:09.538
pathway and RAS signaling, and inhibition of

207
00:12:10.408 --> 00:12:13.868
RASA2 leads to increase in signaling through the RAF

208
00:12:14.068 --> 00:12:16.868
MEKMEK/ERK signaling pathway.

209
00:12:18.508 --> 00:12:22.108
And CRISPR knockout of RAS2 led to

210
00:12:22.248 --> 00:12:26.208
increased signaling in the ERK/MEK pathway

211
00:12:26.388 --> 00:12:27.528
and pathway activation.

212
00:12:28.968 --> 00:12:29.418
And

213
00:12:30.368 --> 00:12:33.768
cells that had loss of RAS2 and activated

214
00:12:34.208 --> 00:12:37.168
pathway signaling were resistant to ruxolitinib.

215
00:12:37.948 --> 00:12:41.268
So this can potentially inform, again, a mechanism of

216
00:12:41.288 --> 00:12:45.168
resistance, and as we think about combination therapies,

217
00:12:45.448 --> 00:12:46.808
a combination of

218
00:12:48.868 --> 00:12:52.518
targeted pathways targeting the JAK pathway and the RAS MAP

219
00:12:52.548 --> 00:12:55.788
kinase pathway in this disease may be particularly efficacious.

220
00:12:57.198 --> 00:12:58.488
So to summarize this part

221
00:12:59.828 --> 00:13:00.188
here,

222
00:13:02.028 --> 00:13:05.748
functional genomic screening identified dependency on JAK1-2

223
00:13:05.888 --> 00:13:08.188
in GLIS2 rearranged AML,

224
00:13:08.988 --> 00:13:12.088
as well as informed mechanisms of resistance to JAK

225
00:13:12.128 --> 00:13:15.838
inhibition and potentially formed effective

226
00:13:15.928 --> 00:13:19.888
combinations that are needed to target really highly aggressive

227
00:13:19.948 --> 00:13:20.928
acute leukemias.

228
00:13:22.888 --> 00:13:26.708
And now to shift towards looking at

229
00:13:28.328 --> 00:13:29.888
cell surface targets.

230
00:13:31.788 --> 00:13:35.388
This is work that was led by Soheil

231
00:13:35.428 --> 00:13:36.008
Meshanchi

232
00:13:36.848 --> 00:13:39.608
in Seattle Children's and Fred Hutch

233
00:13:40.528 --> 00:13:43.658
where they looked at gene expression from over

234
00:13:43.768 --> 00:13:47.608
1,400 pediatric acute myeloid leukemia samples,

235
00:13:48.048 --> 00:13:51.768
as well as 84 healthy controls, to ask what are

236
00:13:51.808 --> 00:13:55.068
the differential targets that are expressed

237
00:13:55.168 --> 00:13:59.128
on specific subtypes of pediatric acute leukemias and

238
00:13:59.148 --> 00:14:00.508
are not present in

239
00:14:01.648 --> 00:14:02.948
normal healthy controls?

240
00:14:04.328 --> 00:14:08.308
And again, focusing on the GLIS2 fusion AML,

241
00:14:09.128 --> 00:14:12.088
you can see that expression of the FLT1

242
00:14:14.208 --> 00:14:17.848
receptor was really high in the GLIS2 fusion

243
00:14:17.928 --> 00:14:21.668
AML compared to the other subtypes of AML that were

244
00:14:21.948 --> 00:14:22.448
present.

245
00:14:23.847 --> 00:14:27.628
So here's where perhaps they got

246
00:14:27.688 --> 00:14:28.968
lucky, as there's

247
00:14:30.008 --> 00:14:31.988
a compound, STRO-02,

248
00:14:32.808 --> 00:14:34.468
that is a FLT1-targeted

249
00:14:35.368 --> 00:14:39.028
antibody-drug conjugate that was being developed by Sutro for

250
00:14:39.108 --> 00:14:41.768
treatment of ovarian cancer and endometrial cancer.

251
00:14:42.848 --> 00:14:46.768
This ADC targets FLT1 and is

252
00:14:47.228 --> 00:14:48.988
bound to a warhead.

253
00:14:50.808 --> 00:14:51.028
In

254
00:14:51.928 --> 00:14:55.048
mice, in acute leukemia models,

255
00:14:55.848 --> 00:14:59.788
a model that expressed high FLT1, you

256
00:14:59.828 --> 00:15:03.408
can see that treatment with STRO-02 led to decrease

257
00:15:03.468 --> 00:15:07.168
in leukemia burden and significantly

258
00:15:07.268 --> 00:15:10.128
prolonged survival of the treated mice.

259
00:15:11.488 --> 00:15:15.228
Perhaps most importantly, given the availability of this

260
00:15:15.468 --> 00:15:18.928
compound, there were 40 young pediatric

261
00:15:18.988 --> 00:15:20.228
patients who were treated

262
00:15:21.748 --> 00:15:24.888
on compassionate use protocols with STRO-02.

263
00:15:25.508 --> 00:15:29.318
And the responses were really quite remarkable for this really, again, highly

264
00:15:29.768 --> 00:15:33.568
aggressive disease, where over 40% of the patients

265
00:15:33.608 --> 00:15:37.508
treated were able to achieve complete remission with low

266
00:15:37.568 --> 00:15:41.028
minimal residual disease. For the patients who achieved

267
00:15:41.408 --> 00:15:42.508
this MRD

268
00:15:43.888 --> 00:15:47.828
negative status, you can see a really quite impressive

269
00:15:48.908 --> 00:15:49.608
survival here.

270
00:15:51.988 --> 00:15:54.988
So here, expanded profiling of cell surface

271
00:15:55.768 --> 00:15:58.478
markers informed a novel target in this really highly

272
00:16:01.108 --> 00:16:03.228
therapy-resistant leukemia

273
00:16:04.208 --> 00:16:07.608
and brought FLT1 expression as a target

274
00:16:08.568 --> 00:16:12.148
to the forefront as we think about ways to treat GLIS2

275
00:16:12.158 --> 00:16:13.168
rearranged AML.

276
00:16:15.148 --> 00:16:18.488
The STRO-02 compound is no longer available,

277
00:16:19.228 --> 00:16:22.648
but this research led to the development of FLT1 CAR T,

278
00:16:23.608 --> 00:16:26.828
which are being tested in patients with GLIS2 rearranged AML.

279
00:16:27.328 --> 00:16:31.267
This is work being led by Katherine Tarlock and Corrin Summers

280
00:16:31.308 --> 00:16:33.148
in Seattle Children's and Fred Hutch.

281
00:16:33.728 --> 00:16:37.568
And I actually recently learned that FLT1 is also really highly expressed in

282
00:16:37.628 --> 00:16:41.288
osteosarcoma, so the next phase of this trial will actually also

283
00:16:41.328 --> 00:16:42.988
include patients with osteosarcoma.

284
00:16:45.468 --> 00:16:49.228
So as the next part, I'll tell you a bit about drug sensitivity

285
00:16:49.348 --> 00:16:52.988
screening and how that could be used to also inform

286
00:16:53.268 --> 00:16:54.648
precision medicine efforts.

287
00:16:55.988 --> 00:16:56.968
A couple of years ago

288
00:16:57.868 --> 00:16:58.188
now,

289
00:16:59.608 --> 00:17:03.068
we partnered with 15 institutions across the United States

290
00:17:03.428 --> 00:17:07.408
to form the LEAP consortium to

291
00:17:07.508 --> 00:17:11.429
study the feasibility of identifying targetable alterations with matched

292
00:17:11.508 --> 00:17:15.168
targeted therapy for pediatric patients with relapsed, refractory, or

293
00:17:15.189 --> 00:17:18.588
high-risk leukemias. This was a study and

294
00:17:18.648 --> 00:17:22.588
consortium that was generously funded by St. Baldrick's Foundation.

295
00:17:25.148 --> 00:17:25.508
And

296
00:17:26.528 --> 00:17:28.429
what we found, you can see here

297
00:17:29.248 --> 00:17:33.068
in the report of the first 153 patients that were enrolled, there

298
00:17:33.108 --> 00:17:35.368
was really a paucity of

299
00:17:36.968 --> 00:17:39.848
immediately actionable alterations.

300
00:17:39.888 --> 00:17:43.628
The most common mutations that were found were actually ones in the RAS pathway,

301
00:17:43.868 --> 00:17:47.208
so KRAS and RAS and PTPN11 most commonly.

302
00:17:48.648 --> 00:17:52.568
We worked with Jeff Tyner's group in Oregon Health Sciences to perform functional

303
00:17:52.648 --> 00:17:54.508
screening of primary patient samples.

304
00:17:55.068 --> 00:17:58.988
Here, leukemia cells were exposed to a number of different compounds

305
00:17:59.308 --> 00:18:02.188
at a range of concentrations, and viability was

306
00:18:02.948 --> 00:18:04.428
assessed after three days.

307
00:18:06.548 --> 00:18:07.588
Focusing on the RAS

308
00:18:08.688 --> 00:18:11.848
signaling pathway, which activates signaling by the

309
00:18:11.868 --> 00:18:15.668
RAF-MEK-ERK pathway and can be inhibited by MEK inhibitors like

310
00:18:15.748 --> 00:18:19.668
trametinib and selumetinib, you can see that samples that had the RAS

311
00:18:19.748 --> 00:18:22.928
pathway mutations were particularly sensitive to this drug.

312
00:18:23.388 --> 00:18:27.048
But again, there were some without the mutation that were also quite

313
00:18:27.328 --> 00:18:30.932
sensitive.A single drug is really unlikely to

314
00:18:30.992 --> 00:18:34.932
cure acute leukemia. And for some samples where there were

315
00:18:34.992 --> 00:18:38.652
enough cells, we were able to look at combinations, combining the MEK

316
00:18:38.692 --> 00:18:42.092
inhibitor trametinib with venetoclax, a BCL2 inhibitor.

317
00:18:42.592 --> 00:18:46.162
And you can see a trend towards combinatorial

318
00:18:46.192 --> 00:18:49.992
efficacy. In acute lymphoblastic leukemia cell

319
00:18:50.032 --> 00:18:51.272
lines, where we have more

320
00:18:52.112 --> 00:18:53.912
cells available, unlimited cells,

321
00:18:54.792 --> 00:18:58.772
we were able to test the combination of trametinib and venetoclax and show

322
00:18:58.812 --> 00:18:59.912
significant synergy.

323
00:19:01.892 --> 00:19:05.492
We then turned to a model of a highly aggressive

324
00:19:06.092 --> 00:19:09.132
B-ALL, one that's defined by this

325
00:19:09.172 --> 00:19:12.172
TCF3-HLF fusion. Again,

326
00:19:13.352 --> 00:19:16.922
going back to the transcription factor

327
00:19:17.432 --> 00:19:21.332
phenomenon. This is a rare subtype of B-ALL that

328
00:19:21.392 --> 00:19:23.892
unfortunately is almost universally

329
00:19:25.072 --> 00:19:25.472
fatal.

330
00:19:26.772 --> 00:19:30.532
In the PDX model, patient-derived xenograft model of

331
00:19:30.832 --> 00:19:33.422
this subtype of B-ALL,

332
00:19:34.932 --> 00:19:37.882
once this leukemia was established,

333
00:19:38.832 --> 00:19:40.132
the mice were treated with

334
00:19:41.192 --> 00:19:43.232
venetoclax or imatinib, or the combination.

335
00:19:43.592 --> 00:19:47.212
This was work done in collaboration and at

336
00:19:47.672 --> 00:19:48.972
Sarah Taizan's lab at CHOP.

337
00:19:50.032 --> 00:19:53.732
And you can see here that, again, the combination led to a

338
00:19:53.772 --> 00:19:56.952
significant decrease in leukemia burden.

339
00:19:59.432 --> 00:20:03.142
So here we were able to show that RAS pathway mutations present a targetable

340
00:20:03.312 --> 00:20:07.172
alteration in high-risk pediatric acute leukemia and

341
00:20:07.372 --> 00:20:10.752
used this drug sensitivity testing to

342
00:20:11.392 --> 00:20:14.772
show that a combination of venetoclax with a MEK inhibitor may be

343
00:20:14.792 --> 00:20:17.172
effective in high-risk B-ALL models.

344
00:20:18.232 --> 00:20:22.112
Overall, integration of genomic profiling and drug sensitivity testing can

345
00:20:22.172 --> 00:20:25.972
uncover therapeutic combinations, and there are a number of groups

346
00:20:26.012 --> 00:20:29.712
now in the United States and in Europe that are working

347
00:20:30.092 --> 00:20:33.832
very hard to try to bring this type of screening to

348
00:20:33.872 --> 00:20:37.392
patient care and to really select therapies for patients.

349
00:20:38.272 --> 00:20:41.992
So I'm hopeful that in the next years, we'll be able to actually

350
00:20:42.092 --> 00:20:43.132
use some of these screening

351
00:20:43.972 --> 00:20:45.632
approaches even more clinically.

352
00:20:47.332 --> 00:20:51.282
So today, to conclude, I showed you a couple of examples of how

353
00:20:51.292 --> 00:20:54.812
we can use functional genomic screening, surface target

354
00:20:54.832 --> 00:20:58.452
identification, and drug sensitivity screening to think about drugging the

355
00:20:58.492 --> 00:21:00.092
undruggable and identify,

356
00:21:01.292 --> 00:21:05.212
perhaps not specific targets, but sensitivities of cancer cells that could

357
00:21:05.232 --> 00:21:05.752
be used

358
00:21:07.392 --> 00:21:08.132
therapeutically.

359
00:21:09.732 --> 00:21:13.672
So I thank you for your attention. I'm really grateful, of course, to

360
00:21:13.712 --> 00:21:17.232
the patients and families who participate in a lot of our clinical

361
00:21:17.272 --> 00:21:20.912
trials in my lab, and a number of our collaborators

362
00:21:20.992 --> 00:21:23.391
and funding sources. Thank you.

