00:24:02.652 --> 00:24:06.592
present today. And I'm excited to talk to you a little bit about a

410
00:24:06.672 --> 00:24:09.192
druggable target, Bruton's tyrosine kinase.

411
00:24:09.652 --> 00:24:13.392
And we'll talk about BTK inhibitor resistance in chronic lymphocytic

412
00:24:13.402 --> 00:24:16.372
leukemia, implications for therapeutic sequencing.

413
00:24:19.652 --> 00:24:23.504
So these are the objectives for the talk today.So for those of

414
00:24:23.544 --> 00:24:27.144
you who aren't as familiar with CLL or don't think about the B-cell

415
00:24:27.184 --> 00:24:31.164
receptor pathway all the time, this is just a little schematic for you

416
00:24:31.244 --> 00:24:33.244
of the B-cell receptor signaling pathway.

417
00:24:33.944 --> 00:24:37.664
And so in a normal B cell, the B-cell receptor is ligated by an

418
00:24:37.744 --> 00:24:41.564
antigen, and depending on the nature of that antigen and the

419
00:24:41.604 --> 00:24:45.464
maturation status of the B cell, a number of things can happen that you

420
00:24:45.504 --> 00:24:48.924
could get activation, proliferation, or even anergy or

421
00:24:48.964 --> 00:24:49.944
apoptosis.

422
00:24:50.824 --> 00:24:54.823
In CLL, there is very minimal interaction with the CLL

423
00:24:54.884 --> 00:24:58.824
cell and the outside environment, although multiple members of the

424
00:24:58.864 --> 00:25:02.064
BCR pathway, including BTK, are upregulated and

425
00:25:02.104 --> 00:25:05.784
constitutively active. And this leads only, in this case,

426
00:25:05.884 --> 00:25:09.634
to survival and proliferation through the AKT pathway and

427
00:25:09.724 --> 00:25:11.944
NF-kappa V and the MAP kinase pathway.

428
00:25:13.504 --> 00:25:13.564
The

429
00:25:14.804 --> 00:25:17.744
first iterations of drugs to target

430
00:25:18.244 --> 00:25:22.184
BTK are the covalent BTK inhibitors, the first-in-class

431
00:25:22.204 --> 00:25:26.074
molecule ibrutinib, and then the second generation, acalabrutinib

432
00:25:26.104 --> 00:25:30.034
and zanubrutinib. These three are all covalent inhibitors that

433
00:25:30.064 --> 00:25:32.784
bind BTK at the cysteine 41 site.

434
00:25:34.214 --> 00:25:38.004
And covalent BTK inhibitors are extremely effective in CLL and

435
00:25:38.024 --> 00:25:41.684
really have revolutionized the way that we treat this disease as well as many

436
00:25:41.764 --> 00:25:43.364
other B-cell malignancies.

437
00:25:44.344 --> 00:25:46.424
On the left here we have the

438
00:25:47.364 --> 00:25:51.134
seminal study of ibrutinib, the RESONATE-2 trial, which is

439
00:25:51.184 --> 00:25:55.144
actually the only one that has been going on long enough to give us a median

440
00:25:55.224 --> 00:25:59.084
progression-free survival. So here we have seen in frontline

441
00:25:59.204 --> 00:26:02.904
CLL that the median PFS with ibrutinib is 8.9 years.

442
00:26:03.524 --> 00:26:07.234
Acalabrutinib and zanubrutinib, the second-generation molecules, were designed to

443
00:26:07.284 --> 00:26:11.044
be more selective for BTK, and with the

444
00:26:11.064 --> 00:26:15.024
idea that this would increase the tolerability of the drugs with

445
00:26:15.084 --> 00:26:18.884
less alternative target or off-target effects, and also potentially

446
00:26:18.964 --> 00:26:21.804
be more effective as they are a little more potent.

447
00:26:22.604 --> 00:26:26.364
These ones, the studies have not gone on long enough to give us a median

448
00:26:26.404 --> 00:26:30.364
PFS yet, but with acalabrutinib here in the ELEVATE

449
00:26:30.404 --> 00:26:34.284
TN study, we have a 62% progression-free survival rate

450
00:26:34.324 --> 00:26:38.204
at six years. With zanubrutinib in the SEQUOIA study down here, we

451
00:26:38.264 --> 00:26:41.723
have a 75.8% PFS at five years.

452
00:26:43.344 --> 00:26:47.084
And then the covalent BTK inhibitors are also effective in relapsed CLL,

453
00:26:47.164 --> 00:26:50.984
although the median PFSs, as you would expect, are not quite as long as we

454
00:26:51.064 --> 00:26:52.424
see in frontline disease.

455
00:26:53.484 --> 00:26:57.124
Here we have two trials that compare a second-generation BTK

456
00:26:57.184 --> 00:27:00.473
inhibitor to ibrutinib. The ELEVATE RR study compared

457
00:27:00.564 --> 00:27:04.524
acalabrutinib to ibrutinib in high-risk relapsed/refractory

458
00:27:04.584 --> 00:27:07.984
CLL, and this study demonstrated non-inferiority of

459
00:27:08.084 --> 00:27:11.944
acalabrutinib to ibrutinib. Down here we have the ALPINe study, which

460
00:27:11.954 --> 00:27:15.904
compared ibrutinib and zanubrutinib head-to-head in an unselected

461
00:27:15.984 --> 00:27:19.724
relapsed/refractory patient population, showing zanubrutinib to

462
00:27:19.804 --> 00:27:20.084
be

463
00:27:21.144 --> 00:27:23.504
superior to ibrutinib in terms of PFS.

464
00:27:24.324 --> 00:27:28.284
And unlike the frontline studies where we see basically

465
00:27:28.424 --> 00:27:31.874
all patients will respond and have durable remissions, in

466
00:27:31.874 --> 00:27:35.504
relapsed/refractory disease, we do see increased relevance to our

467
00:27:35.524 --> 00:27:37.804
traditional prognostic factors in the disease.

468
00:27:38.904 --> 00:27:42.604
At Ohio State, we had the opportunity to take care of a lot of patients treated

469
00:27:42.644 --> 00:27:46.394
with these covalent BTK inhibitors, and so a few years ago looked at

470
00:27:46.524 --> 00:27:49.904
456 patients treated with ibrutinib

471
00:27:50.224 --> 00:27:53.624
to look at baseline characteristics independently

472
00:27:53.684 --> 00:27:55.784
associated with progression-free survival.

473
00:27:56.274 --> 00:28:00.014
And using multivariable models, we see that higher Rai stage at

474
00:28:00.084 --> 00:28:03.964
diagnosis, the presence of previously treated

475
00:28:04.004 --> 00:28:07.884
CLL, a worsening ECOG performance status, higher

476
00:28:08.084 --> 00:28:12.024
LDH at baseline, and increasing karyotypic complexity

477
00:28:12.033 --> 00:28:15.464
are all associated with a shorter PFS with this drug.

478
00:28:16.984 --> 00:28:20.784
So when we think about how patients do become resistant to the

479
00:28:20.804 --> 00:28:24.564
BTK inhibitors in CLL, with covalent BTK inhibitors, the

480
00:28:24.604 --> 00:28:28.184
primary mechanism of resistance is acquisition of mutations

481
00:28:28.524 --> 00:28:32.504
in either BTK itself or in the immediate downstream target of

482
00:28:32.544 --> 00:28:36.364
BTK, PLC gamma 2. And in general, we'll talk about this in more

483
00:28:36.404 --> 00:28:40.044
detail, but in general, BTK mutations impair drug binding,

484
00:28:41.204 --> 00:28:44.704
and PLC gamma 2 mutations activate downstream signaling.

485
00:28:45.564 --> 00:28:49.144
So the first mutation that was identified is the cysteine to serine mutation,

486
00:28:49.244 --> 00:28:52.964
C41S, and so this is at the binding site of the drug and actually

487
00:28:53.004 --> 00:28:56.764
causes ibrutinib to inhibit BTK reversibly rather than

488
00:28:57.004 --> 00:29:00.004
irreversibly. And we can see that in the experiments here.

489
00:29:00.044 --> 00:29:03.484
Over here on the left, we have recombinant

490
00:29:03.564 --> 00:29:07.464
protein, either wild type or C41, exposed to

491
00:29:07.504 --> 00:29:11.304
ibrutinib in either a manner where you just give the drug continuously

492
00:29:11.384 --> 00:29:14.964
or wash the drug out. And you can see that with wild-type

493
00:29:14.984 --> 00:29:18.964
BTK, the first two bars here, it doesn't matter if you leave the drug in

494
00:29:19.004 --> 00:29:22.804
or if you wash it out, you inhibit both BTK and downstream

495
00:29:22.844 --> 00:29:23.964
ERK phosphorylation,

496
00:29:25.164 --> 00:29:27.884
as you would expect for an irreversible inhibitor.

497
00:29:28.444 --> 00:29:31.884
With C41S BTK, on the other hand, if you leave the drug in

498
00:29:31.924 --> 00:29:35.764
continuously, the dark blue lines here, you actually still can

499
00:29:35.804 --> 00:29:39.704
inhibit BTK and ERK phosphorylation to some degree, but if you wash

500
00:29:39.764 --> 00:29:42.844
the drug out, that inhibition is abrogated.

501
00:29:43.524 --> 00:29:45.444
We can see that in a patient sample over here.

502
00:29:45.524 --> 00:29:46.944
So this is a patient who

503
00:29:47.764 --> 00:29:51.584
was treated with ibrutinib. We have a sample at baseline and then at the time of

504
00:29:51.644 --> 00:29:54.474
relapse, where a C41S mutation was detected.

505
00:29:55.004 --> 00:29:58.844
And you can see, then we exposed the cells to ibrutinib, again,

506
00:29:58.884 --> 00:30:02.844
wash out or continuous. And at baseline with wild-type

507
00:30:02.884 --> 00:30:06.764
BTK, whether you leave the drug in or if you wash it out, you can inhibit

508
00:30:06.784 --> 00:30:10.444
BTK phosphorylation. But in the presence of a C41S

509
00:30:10.484 --> 00:30:14.144
mutation, if you leave the drug in continuously, you can inhibit BTK

510
00:30:14.224 --> 00:30:17.924
phosphorylation, but as soon as you wash the drug out, that phosphorylation

511
00:30:17.964 --> 00:30:21.744
returns.We also see that the PLC gamma

512
00:30:21.864 --> 00:30:25.264
2 mutations, there's a number of hotspot mutations that have been

513
00:30:25.324 --> 00:30:29.284
identified, but they mostly share the same characteristic that

514
00:30:29.324 --> 00:30:32.064
they are a potentially activating mutation.

515
00:30:33.104 --> 00:30:35.844
So in cell lines with two of the more common ones,

516
00:30:36.084 --> 00:30:39.894
R665W and L845F, we see that

517
00:30:39.924 --> 00:30:43.884
downstream phosphorylation of AKT and ERK

518
00:30:43.894 --> 00:30:47.524
remains present even in the presence of ibrutinib.

519
00:30:47.564 --> 00:30:51.504
We can see that in a patient sample over here, again, taken at the time of

520
00:30:51.524 --> 00:30:55.474
relapse where an R665W PLC gamma 2 mutation was

521
00:30:55.504 --> 00:30:58.784
identified. We see that we can actually still inhibit BTK

522
00:30:58.804 --> 00:31:02.604
phosphorylation as you would expect with ibrutinib, but the downstream

523
00:31:02.684 --> 00:31:04.684
PLC gamma 2 remains active.

524
00:31:06.924 --> 00:31:09.624
Then this is looking at calcium flux here.

525
00:31:09.784 --> 00:31:12.264
So when you add the IgM, you get calcium flux.

526
00:31:12.624 --> 00:31:16.604
Green here is wild type BTK where you see

527
00:31:16.704 --> 00:31:20.524
a calcium flux that then can be inhibited if you add ibrutinib

528
00:31:20.604 --> 00:31:21.004
to it.

529
00:31:22.384 --> 00:31:25.724
With either the R665W or L845F

530
00:31:25.764 --> 00:31:29.664
mutations, we see both augmented and sustained calcium flux that

531
00:31:29.704 --> 00:31:31.604
are not affected if you add ibrutinib.

532
00:31:33.024 --> 00:31:36.324
Again, demonstrating that these are activating mutations.

533
00:31:37.384 --> 00:31:41.204
So many centers have now demonstrated that these

534
00:31:41.244 --> 00:31:44.044
mutations are present in patients where

535
00:31:44.244 --> 00:31:47.924
patients become resistant to

536
00:31:47.944 --> 00:31:51.724
BTK inhibitors. These are some data from a collaboration with

537
00:31:51.784 --> 00:31:53.784
Pharmacyclics who made ibrutinib,

538
00:31:54.844 --> 00:31:58.724
where we looked at samples from company studies for patients at the time of

539
00:31:58.784 --> 00:32:02.124
relapse, and we divided those relapses into Richter's

540
00:32:02.144 --> 00:32:05.904
transformation, which is a transformation of CLL to a more aggressive type of

541
00:32:05.924 --> 00:32:06.464
lymphoma,

542
00:32:07.404 --> 00:32:11.244
relapse which was typified by increased lymphadenopathy

543
00:32:11.504 --> 00:32:15.364
only, where we did not see elevation of the lymphocyte count, or the

544
00:32:15.404 --> 00:32:18.984
most common, where we actually see increase in the blood

545
00:32:19.024 --> 00:32:22.644
lymphocytes at the time of relapse, and then looked for the presence of these

546
00:32:22.704 --> 00:32:26.464
mutations. And you can see that when patients have increased

547
00:32:26.504 --> 00:32:29.243
lymphocytes in their blood at the time of relapse,

548
00:32:30.083 --> 00:32:33.404
81% of those patients had BTK mutations and

549
00:32:33.424 --> 00:32:37.144
19% had PLC gamma 2 mutations. This is a little bit

550
00:32:37.204 --> 00:32:40.944
lower in patients where we don't see elevated lymphocyte count

551
00:32:41.104 --> 00:32:42.304
at the time of relapse.

552
00:32:43.364 --> 00:32:46.724
The group at NHLBI with Adrian Wiestner has actually shown

553
00:32:47.344 --> 00:32:49.724
that there may be a compartment effect to this.

554
00:32:49.804 --> 00:32:53.664
So they were able to take samples from the blood, lymph nodes, and

555
00:32:53.724 --> 00:32:57.653
bone marrow at the same patient at the same time point, and they found

556
00:32:57.684 --> 00:33:00.984
that the allelic frequencies of these mutations are actually quite different in

557
00:33:01.004 --> 00:33:04.664
these different compartments, and even sometimes you can see a mutation in the

558
00:33:04.724 --> 00:33:07.584
lymph node, but not in the blood or bone marrow or vice versa.

559
00:33:08.584 --> 00:33:11.624
So suggesting a potential reason why we see lower

560
00:33:13.244 --> 00:33:15.593
presence of the mutations in the blood in these patients.

561
00:33:16.014 --> 00:33:19.944
And then Richter's transformation is only rarely associated with these mutations.

562
00:33:22.284 --> 00:33:26.004
So we know that their mutations can be seen at the time of relapse,

563
00:33:26.644 --> 00:33:30.384
and actually then have been able to demonstrate that these resistance

564
00:33:30.444 --> 00:33:34.164
mutations actually can be detected far in advance of relapse and can even

565
00:33:34.204 --> 00:33:38.084
be evaluated prospectively. So here on the left, we

566
00:33:38.104 --> 00:33:42.054
have some data from the NHLBI, on the right data from Ohio State,

567
00:33:42.784 --> 00:33:44.124
where we took samples

568
00:33:45.064 --> 00:33:46.114
from the time of

569
00:33:46.944 --> 00:33:50.444
relapse looking backward, and were able to see that we could

570
00:33:50.524 --> 00:33:54.484
identify BTK or PLC gamma 2 mutations at a median of 9 to

571
00:33:54.504 --> 00:33:58.404
12 months prior to relapse, suggesting that there may be a window for

572
00:33:58.484 --> 00:34:02.344
therapeutic intervention there before a patient actually would clinically

573
00:34:02.384 --> 00:34:03.564
relapse on these drugs.

574
00:34:05.184 --> 00:34:08.935
Acalabrutinib, the second-generation BTK inhibitor, has similar

575
00:34:08.984 --> 00:34:11.004
mechanisms of resistance to ibrutinib.

576
00:34:11.665 --> 00:34:15.304
These are data from the ELEVATE RR study, which compared

577
00:34:15.344 --> 00:34:17.584
acalabrutinib to ibrutinib head-to-head.

578
00:34:18.024 --> 00:34:21.964
And we actually found that there were higher rates of BTK

579
00:34:22.024 --> 00:34:25.824
C41 mutations in acalabrutinib-treated patients compared with

580
00:34:25.884 --> 00:34:28.225
ibrutinib-treated patients in this group.

581
00:34:28.484 --> 00:34:32.104
However, more PLC gamma 2 mutations were identified in ibrutinib-treated

582
00:34:32.185 --> 00:34:34.144
patients compared to acalabrutinib-treated.

583
00:34:34.765 --> 00:34:38.384
We also saw emergence of a new mutation, T474I, which is a

584
00:34:38.504 --> 00:34:42.404
gatekeeper mutation. And in this study, this was only observed

585
00:34:42.424 --> 00:34:45.824
in acalabrutinib-treated patients, and actually was only seen in

586
00:34:46.104 --> 00:34:48.643
patients who also had a C41S mutation.

587
00:34:50.044 --> 00:34:53.784
Zanubrutinib is the newest of the covalent BTK inhibitors, so the data on

588
00:34:53.844 --> 00:34:57.824
resistance is the most limited. This is a smaller study from a

589
00:34:57.884 --> 00:35:01.854
group in Australia who looked at ibrutinib- and zanubrutinib-treated patients at

590
00:35:01.884 --> 00:35:05.704
the time of relapse. They did find C41S mutations in both

591
00:35:05.744 --> 00:35:08.904
ibrutinib- and zanubrutinib-treated patients, although more commonly in the

592
00:35:08.924 --> 00:35:12.554
ibrutinib-treated patients. But actually found a new

593
00:35:12.584 --> 00:35:15.964
mutation, L528W, which is a kinase-impaired

594
00:35:15.984 --> 00:35:19.424
mutation, and this was primarily seen in zanubrutinib-treated

595
00:35:19.524 --> 00:35:22.324
patients and only rarely in ibrutinib-treated patients.

596
00:35:23.784 --> 00:35:27.224
So to recap, with our covalent BTK inhibitors, we do see

597
00:35:28.084 --> 00:35:31.664
similar and distinct patterns of relapse of these BTK mutations.

598
00:35:31.724 --> 00:35:35.444
So with ibrutinib, we see primarily C41 mutations in BTK.

599
00:35:36.044 --> 00:35:39.364
With acalabrutinib, we see C41 and T474.

600
00:35:39.764 --> 00:35:43.384
And then with zanubrutinib, C41 and L528W

601
00:35:43.424 --> 00:35:44.084
mutations.

602
00:35:45.604 --> 00:35:49.554
So importantly to this idea of therapeutic sequencing, we see that

603
00:35:49.604 --> 00:35:53.104
even in the presence of relapse

604
00:35:53.244 --> 00:35:56.964
after covalent BTK inhibitors and also in the presence or

605
00:35:57.064 --> 00:36:00.904
absence of these mutations, we do see that the B-cell receptor pathway

606
00:36:00.944 --> 00:36:04.304
remains upregulated and active. So this is

607
00:36:04.584 --> 00:36:08.424
single-cell sequencing data from three patients at baseline and relapse looking

608
00:36:08.504 --> 00:36:08.724
at

609
00:36:09.664 --> 00:36:12.924
a BCR score, and you can see here that

610
00:36:13.244 --> 00:36:16.984
compared to baseline at relapse, if anything, the BCR score is even a little

611
00:36:17.004 --> 00:36:20.724
bit higher, suggesting that these proteins are still going to be relevant,

612
00:36:21.244 --> 00:36:25.194
and importantly suggesting that repeated targeting of BTK may be effective

613
00:36:25.224 --> 00:36:29.108
if you have a drug that can overcome these resistance mutations.And

614
00:36:29.148 --> 00:36:32.828
so that led the way to the development of non-covalent

615
00:36:32.888 --> 00:36:36.428
BTK inhibitors. There are a few in clinical development.

616
00:36:36.528 --> 00:36:39.828
Pirtobrutinib is the furthest along, having received FDA approval.

617
00:36:40.248 --> 00:36:43.948
Nemtabrutinib is in Phase III clinical trials, and these sort of typify

618
00:36:44.568 --> 00:36:48.388
this idea of a BTK inhibitor that binds

619
00:36:48.448 --> 00:36:52.268
reversibly rather than irreversibly and does not use that C481

620
00:36:52.348 --> 00:36:56.248
site. So was hypothesized to be effective even in the presence

621
00:36:56.288 --> 00:36:58.708
of C481 resistance mutations.

622
00:36:59.788 --> 00:37:02.128
These two drugs are fairly different from each other.

623
00:37:02.188 --> 00:37:06.148
So pirtobrutinib, as you see here from the kino map, is extremely

624
00:37:06.268 --> 00:37:10.108
selective. And that has led to it being very well-tolerated as well.

625
00:37:10.548 --> 00:37:14.348
And in vitro has similar inhibition with

626
00:37:14.448 --> 00:37:18.248
wild-type and C481S BTK. Nemtabrutinib, on the other hand, is

627
00:37:18.308 --> 00:37:21.968
actually a very non-specific molecule and is a pan-Src and

628
00:37:22.008 --> 00:37:25.868
pan-Tec kinase inhibitor. This actually leads to it being

629
00:37:25.888 --> 00:37:29.828
relatively cytotoxic to CLL cells, more cytotoxic than we see

630
00:37:29.868 --> 00:37:33.487
with most other of the BTK inhibitors, and in this

631
00:37:33.808 --> 00:37:37.708
experiment was effective even in the setting of ibrutinib-resistant

632
00:37:37.828 --> 00:37:38.228
CLL.

633
00:37:39.848 --> 00:37:41.368
So with pirtobrutinib,

634
00:37:42.908 --> 00:37:45.828
I'm going to focus on pirtobrutinib here since it's the furthest along in

635
00:37:45.848 --> 00:37:49.548
development. We do see very high clinical efficacy in

636
00:37:49.568 --> 00:37:52.648
patients after treatment with a covalent BTK inhibitor.

637
00:37:53.268 --> 00:37:56.648
So these are some data from the Phase I/II clinical trial.

638
00:37:56.688 --> 00:38:00.088
On the left here we have a waterfall plot where you can see that almost all

639
00:38:00.108 --> 00:38:03.888
patients had shrinkage in their lymph nodes when treated with pirtobrutinib.

640
00:38:03.948 --> 00:38:06.248
The overall response rate here is over 80%.

641
00:38:06.948 --> 00:38:10.118
Looking at progression-free survival on the right here, the median PFS was

642
00:38:10.128 --> 00:38:13.938
19.6 months. So a very effective drug, although

643
00:38:13.968 --> 00:38:17.688
the durability of that efficacy in relapsed CLL is not as

644
00:38:17.928 --> 00:38:19.288
long as we see with the covalent

645
00:38:21.088 --> 00:38:22.108
BTK inhibitors.

646
00:38:24.248 --> 00:38:27.427
So at the same time that pirtobrutinib was being developed, there were people

647
00:38:27.488 --> 00:38:31.108
studying what was leading to resistance with pirtobrutinib.

648
00:38:31.148 --> 00:38:34.748
This is the first data to come out of that, coming from Omar

649
00:38:34.788 --> 00:38:38.108
Abdel-Wahab's group. And they looked at

650
00:38:39.528 --> 00:38:42.448
nine patients, I believe, who had relapsed on

651
00:38:42.508 --> 00:38:46.108
pirtobrutinib and found that most of the patients had acquired

652
00:38:46.168 --> 00:38:49.468
mutations in BTK at non-C481 sites.

653
00:38:50.448 --> 00:38:54.228
So some of the more common mutations that were identified are this

654
00:38:54.328 --> 00:38:58.168
gatekeeper mutation, T474I. Again, we saw that previously

655
00:38:58.208 --> 00:39:00.058
with acalabrutinib-treated patients.

656
00:39:00.618 --> 00:39:04.488
And then this kinase-impaired mutation, L528W, again

657
00:39:04.528 --> 00:39:07.868
previously seen also in zanubrutinib-treated patients.

658
00:39:07.928 --> 00:39:11.548
A number of other kinase-impaired mutations have been observed, and then

659
00:39:11.628 --> 00:39:15.028
other kind of mutants of that gatekeeper site as well.

660
00:39:15.808 --> 00:39:19.268
Importantly though, and interestingly, the C481 mutation, which

661
00:39:19.308 --> 00:39:23.168
many patients came on to the study with, actually either

662
00:39:23.178 --> 00:39:26.997
decreased in allelic frequency or even disappeared entirely in the blood in

663
00:39:27.048 --> 00:39:28.848
these patients at the time of relapse.

664
00:39:31.388 --> 00:39:34.248
So what do we do after non-covalent BTK inhibitors?

665
00:39:34.848 --> 00:39:38.808
Luckily, people had already started to work on these BTK degraders,

666
00:39:39.728 --> 00:39:43.628
which have the capability to overcome many of these BTK

667
00:39:43.708 --> 00:39:46.058
resistance mutations that we have been seeing.

668
00:39:47.128 --> 00:39:49.648
Two of the furthest along, there's a number of these in development, two of the

669
00:39:49.748 --> 00:39:51.888
furthest along are Bexarotenoag and

670
00:39:51.948 --> 00:39:55.728
BGB16673. And you can see here from their clinical

671
00:39:56.028 --> 00:39:59.398
data in the Phase I clinical trials, they both have been extremely

672
00:39:59.468 --> 00:40:03.148
effective in the setting of kinase inhibitor-resistant

673
00:40:03.268 --> 00:40:06.928
CLL. Many of these patients have been treated with both covalent and non-covalent

674
00:40:06.968 --> 00:40:10.008
BTK inhibitors, in fact. And with the

675
00:40:10.028 --> 00:40:13.988
Bexarotenoag, the median PFS was 22.1 months.

676
00:40:14.148 --> 00:40:17.668
With BGB16673, the 16-month PFS was

677
00:40:17.868 --> 00:40:21.288
65.9%. So suggesting that, again, these are going to be

678
00:40:21.328 --> 00:40:24.548
effective drugs but may not also give those

679
00:40:24.828 --> 00:40:27.548
five-plus year remission durations like we

680
00:40:28.588 --> 00:40:31.268
were seeing with the covalent BTK inhibitors at first.

681
00:40:33.088 --> 00:40:36.728
So resistance to the BTK degraders is still being worked out for the

682
00:40:37.248 --> 00:40:41.068
majority of patients, but one mutation has come up in a

683
00:40:41.148 --> 00:40:44.928
few different clinical sets and has been looked at in more

684
00:40:44.967 --> 00:40:48.467
detail, and this is an A428D mutation in BTK.

685
00:40:49.568 --> 00:40:53.278
This has also been very rarely observed with other kinase inhibitors,

686
00:40:53.328 --> 00:40:57.108
although not seen very often at all, but seems to be more common

687
00:40:57.208 --> 00:40:57.528
with

688
00:40:58.328 --> 00:41:01.948
these degraders. And this mutation actually unfortunately interferes with the

689
00:41:01.988 --> 00:41:05.288
binding pocket and collapses that binding pocket a little bit, which

690
00:41:05.508 --> 00:41:09.448
suggests that it will likely confer resistance to all of the

691
00:41:09.468 --> 00:41:13.088
BTK kinase inhibitors and degraders that are currently in clinical

692
00:41:13.148 --> 00:41:13.788
development.

693
00:41:15.608 --> 00:41:19.228
So when we think about how we could use this information to sequence,

694
00:41:19.988 --> 00:41:23.828
there is certainly a straightforward pathway that we can think about that may

695
00:41:23.908 --> 00:41:27.568
be applicable to the majority of CLL patients, especially ones that are

696
00:41:27.648 --> 00:41:31.628
older when they start treatment. And this is where you could use a covalent

697
00:41:31.648 --> 00:41:35.238
BTK inhibitor in the frontline setting, continue it until

698
00:41:35.288 --> 00:41:38.948
progression, which hopefully is going to be nine-plus years.

699
00:41:38.988 --> 00:41:42.848
At the emergence of likely a C481 BTK mutation, you

700
00:41:42.928 --> 00:41:46.768
would switch the patient to a non-covalent BTK inhibitor, hopefully get a

701
00:41:46.828 --> 00:41:48.788
couple year remission duration out of that.

702
00:41:49.348 --> 00:41:53.028
Likely acquisition or expansion of mutations such as

703
00:41:53.068 --> 00:41:57.008
T474I or L528W, and then move on to a

704
00:41:57.028 --> 00:42:00.958
BTK degrader. Again, maybe a couple year remission duration, and

705
00:42:00.988 --> 00:42:03.968
then potentially developing mutations either at this

706
00:42:04.088 --> 00:42:06.568
A428D or other sites.

707
00:42:07.548 --> 00:42:08.478
And so this would,

708
00:42:09.368 --> 00:42:12.898
in a perfect world, give you about 13 years of treatment for an individual

709
00:42:12.988 --> 00:42:14.868
patient, and that doesn't even

710
00:42:15.928 --> 00:42:19.538
use our other major pathway in CLL that can be targeted, the

711
00:42:19.568 --> 00:42:23.528
BCL2 pathway. Although, of course, nothing is perfect, and there are

712
00:42:23.548 --> 00:42:25.018
a lot of challenges to this

713
00:42:25.848 --> 00:42:29.368
approach. And of course, there can be multiple mutant clones in an

714
00:42:29.408 --> 00:42:33.248
individual patient. PLC gamma-2 mutations are

715
00:42:33.268 --> 00:42:36.688
likely going to be a challenge with the non-covalent BTK inhibitors, though may be

716
00:42:36.728 --> 00:42:40.638
overcome with the degraders. And then new mutations, maybe after

717
00:42:40.648 --> 00:42:44.588
a BTK degrader, or mutations that can occur

718
00:42:44.628 --> 00:42:48.308
in other parts along this pathway that may render other

719
00:42:48.328 --> 00:42:52.232
drugs ineffective.So I think that there's

720
00:42:52.272 --> 00:42:56.162
a few questions and a few kind of thoughts going into the future that may

721
00:42:56.212 --> 00:42:59.972
help us to better understand how we could sequence for individual

722
00:43:00.072 --> 00:43:03.672
patients, if we can use all of these classes of drugs, if we can use

723
00:43:03.732 --> 00:43:05.692
combinations that might be helpful.

724
00:43:05.752 --> 00:43:09.632
I think the first question that people are working on is whether these BTK

725
00:43:09.652 --> 00:43:12.612
mutations disappear without drug pressure.

726
00:43:13.452 --> 00:43:17.152
And this probably will depend a little bit on the type of mutation.

727
00:43:17.252 --> 00:43:20.492
So with the C481S mutation, I showed you that with

728
00:43:20.532 --> 00:43:24.412
pirtobrutinib, that can often decrease with treatment and even

729
00:43:24.472 --> 00:43:28.332
disappear even at the time of relapse after taking pirtobrutinib.

730
00:43:29.172 --> 00:43:32.952
But in studies looking at venetoclax after BTK inhibitors,

731
00:43:33.112 --> 00:43:36.712
usually that C481S mutation persists even after treatment with

732
00:43:36.752 --> 00:43:37.612
venetoclax.

733
00:43:38.792 --> 00:43:39.592
On the other hand,

734
00:43:40.912 --> 00:43:44.872
A428D and some of these other kinase-impaired mutations may

735
00:43:44.932 --> 00:43:48.752
actually have less of a survival advantage in the absence of a drug than

736
00:43:48.792 --> 00:43:51.452
a C481S or the gatekeeper mutations.

737
00:43:51.862 --> 00:43:55.812
And it's a little bit less clear how much persistence we are going to

738
00:43:55.912 --> 00:43:57.412
see in the absence of drug.

739
00:43:58.712 --> 00:44:02.332
My guess, though, is that all of these mutations, even if we can't detect

740
00:44:02.432 --> 00:44:05.972
them in the blood, will persist at some low level, so

741
00:44:06.072 --> 00:44:09.752
probably preventing us from getting durable remissions by using

742
00:44:09.792 --> 00:44:11.852
these drugs in a circle.

743
00:44:13.192 --> 00:44:16.672
But you may be able to come back to a drug like pirtobrutinib

744
00:44:16.792 --> 00:44:20.692
or even a degrader or something after treatment with another class of drug

745
00:44:20.732 --> 00:44:23.012
and have at least a short remission duration.

746
00:44:25.432 --> 00:44:29.272
And another question that is sort of top of everybody's mind

747
00:44:29.292 --> 00:44:32.812
right now is what would happen if we sequenced pirtobrutinib first?

748
00:44:33.572 --> 00:44:36.902
So this is because of two phase 3 clinical trials that were

749
00:44:37.152 --> 00:44:41.072
presented and published at the end of last year, both looking at

750
00:44:41.092 --> 00:44:43.152
pirtobrutinib in the frontline setting.

751
00:44:43.172 --> 00:44:46.982
One of these is BRU-IN-314, which is a trial head-to-head of

752
00:44:47.032 --> 00:44:48.732
pirtobrutinib versus ibrutinib.

753
00:44:49.142 --> 00:44:52.152
And in this study, one-third of the patients were treatment naive.

754
00:44:52.672 --> 00:44:56.632
And here we saw a superior overall response rate

755
00:44:56.652 --> 00:45:00.592
for pirtobrutinib versus ibrutinib in the entirety of the patient populations

756
00:45:00.632 --> 00:45:04.512
that were treated, as well as an even more striking trend

757
00:45:04.612 --> 00:45:08.442
towards superior overall response rate in the treatment-naive subgroup.

758
00:45:08.992 --> 00:45:12.492
Down here we have a Kaplan-Meier curve of the treatment-naive subgroup.

759
00:45:12.532 --> 00:45:14.752
Again, the follow-up here is very short.

760
00:45:15.392 --> 00:45:19.282
But we do see a trend towards pirtobrutinib having a longer PFS compared

761
00:45:19.312 --> 00:45:22.252
with ibrutinib, which of course is really interesting to see in the frontline

762
00:45:22.792 --> 00:45:23.112
setting.

763
00:45:24.892 --> 00:45:28.302
However, we don't have any data yet regarding the emergence of resistance

764
00:45:28.352 --> 00:45:31.092
mutations in treatment-naive patients with pirtobrutinib.

765
00:45:31.152 --> 00:45:33.772
We don't know what the timing of those is going to be.

766
00:45:33.872 --> 00:45:36.632
We don't know if they're going to be the exact same mutations that we see in

767
00:45:36.712 --> 00:45:38.132
relapsed/refractory CLL.

768
00:45:39.052 --> 00:45:42.932
We do know that some of these mutations that we expect to see, like the gatekeeper

769
00:45:42.972 --> 00:45:46.632
mutations, the kinase-impaired mutations, may make sequencing of a

770
00:45:46.692 --> 00:45:50.572
covalent BTK inhibitor difficult, although maybe not impossible, because it

771
00:45:50.612 --> 00:45:54.112
does seem, at least in vitro, that acalabrutinib has some

772
00:45:54.152 --> 00:45:57.512
activity in the kinase-impaired mutations, whereas

773
00:45:57.572 --> 00:46:00.332
zanubrutinib has some activity in the gatekeeper mutation.

774
00:46:00.432 --> 00:46:04.112
So we don't know, though, are we going to see as long of a

775
00:46:04.132 --> 00:46:05.832
remission if we do things in that order?

776
00:46:07.032 --> 00:46:08.652
So I think until more data emerge,

777
00:46:09.872 --> 00:46:13.572
most of us would reserve frontline pirtobrutinib for the group of

778
00:46:13.612 --> 00:46:16.552
patients who are either older, where you may think that they're only going to need

779
00:46:16.612 --> 00:46:20.512
one or two lines of treatment within their natural lifespan, or those

780
00:46:20.552 --> 00:46:22.612
that are frail that may not tolerate a

781
00:46:23.492 --> 00:46:25.292
covalent BTK inhibitor quite as well.

782
00:46:26.712 --> 00:46:29.792
So what about a dual covalent non-covalent approach?

783
00:46:30.032 --> 00:46:33.492
And so instead of kind of sequencing the drugs, what if there was one drug that

784
00:46:33.552 --> 00:46:34.372
could do both?

785
00:46:35.392 --> 00:46:38.912
So there is a drug currently in development called rockbrutinib or

786
00:46:38.972 --> 00:46:42.772
LP-168 which has this mechanism. So in the

787
00:46:42.792 --> 00:46:46.352
setting of wild-type C481, the drug can bind

788
00:46:46.832 --> 00:46:50.552
irreversibly, just like ibrutinib, acalabrutinib, and zanubrutinib.

789
00:46:51.132 --> 00:46:55.012
However, if C481 is mutated, the drug actually has the ability to form

790
00:46:55.072 --> 00:46:56.912
non-covalent interactions too

791
00:46:57.732 --> 00:47:01.552
and extends pretty deep into the binding pocket and actually does not

792
00:47:01.712 --> 00:47:05.252
interact with any of the other sites that we see resistance

793
00:47:05.292 --> 00:47:06.472
mutations develop in.

794
00:47:07.592 --> 00:47:08.192
In vitro,

795
00:47:09.212 --> 00:47:13.092
rockbrutinib is effective in C481S BTK as well

796
00:47:13.172 --> 00:47:16.492
as T474I and L528W BTK.

797
00:47:17.232 --> 00:47:19.892
And here's some data from the phase 1 clinical trial,

798
00:47:21.092 --> 00:47:24.752
just a waterfall plot showing you that there was lymph node

799
00:47:24.772 --> 00:47:28.132
shrinkage seen in patients treated with multiple covalent BTK

800
00:47:28.152 --> 00:47:32.122
inhibitors, with non-covalent BTK inhibitors, as

801
00:47:32.152 --> 00:47:34.132
well as those treated with venetoclax.

802
00:47:34.662 --> 00:47:37.632
And this drug is now moving to phase 3 clinical trials.

803
00:47:38.732 --> 00:47:42.712
And then the last point I want to bring up is actually a kind

804
00:47:42.752 --> 00:47:46.262
of big point of debate, and this is whether fixed-duration regimens might

805
00:47:46.292 --> 00:47:50.232
prevent resistance mutations. So I showed you a schematic of what might happen

806
00:47:50.272 --> 00:47:53.892
if you treat somebody with CLL for upwards of 13

807
00:47:53.912 --> 00:47:56.972
years, expecting that they're going to be on drug that whole time.

808
00:47:57.972 --> 00:48:01.932
As more and more data comes out with BTK inhibitor plus

809
00:48:01.952 --> 00:48:05.632
BCL-2 inhibitor combinations, we see that this type of

810
00:48:05.672 --> 00:48:09.592
approach is actually extremely active and may give patients the

811
00:48:09.612 --> 00:48:13.592
opportunity to be on albeit a little more aggressive therapy for a little while,

812
00:48:13.712 --> 00:48:17.572
but then have long treatment-free intervals between therapies.

813
00:48:19.792 --> 00:48:23.632
We're relatively new in the idea of sequencing these types of fixed-duration

814
00:48:23.712 --> 00:48:27.472
regimens, so I think most of the data is relatively immature in terms of what's

815
00:48:27.512 --> 00:48:29.752
going to happen if you do this repeatedly.

816
00:48:29.972 --> 00:48:33.492
However, all data suggests that you may be able to re-treat

817
00:48:33.502 --> 00:48:35.352
patients with these types of approaches.

818
00:48:35.432 --> 00:48:35.572
So

819
00:48:36.552 --> 00:48:40.432
one of the studies that we have the most information from

820
00:48:40.472 --> 00:48:44.392
is the CAPTIVATE trial, which is a frontline study of ibrutinib plus venetoclax

821
00:48:44.472 --> 00:48:45.352
given for a year.

822
00:48:46.522 --> 00:48:50.242
And there were 25 patients who, at the time of disease progression, had samples

823
00:48:50.312 --> 00:48:54.292
available. No mutations were observed in either BTK or PLC gamma

824
00:48:54.412 --> 00:48:57.734
2.15 patients were retreated with

825
00:48:57.744 --> 00:49:01.304
ibrutinib, and all of them actually responded to the drug.

826
00:49:01.344 --> 00:49:04.824
And anecdotally, that's what we've seen in the setting of other fixed-duration

827
00:49:04.964 --> 00:49:08.584
regimens like this as well, where after the patient relapses

828
00:49:08.644 --> 00:49:12.584
after their first treatment with either a doublet or a triplet, they can generally

829
00:49:12.624 --> 00:49:16.344
be treated with either BTK inhibitors or BCL-2 inhibitors with

830
00:49:16.404 --> 00:49:16.984
success.

831
00:49:17.964 --> 00:49:20.004
However, I think we would all expect that if you

832
00:49:21.284 --> 00:49:24.284
do this type of approach, you're likely to have a shorter remission duration each

833
00:49:24.324 --> 00:49:27.884
time, and we may in fact see the emergence of these resistance mutations with

834
00:49:27.963 --> 00:49:28.924
repeated exposure.

835
00:49:30.264 --> 00:49:34.204
So to conclude, resistance to BTK inhibitors will be a continued problem

836
00:49:34.244 --> 00:49:37.764
with continuous dosing. Development of alternative kinase

837
00:49:37.884 --> 00:49:41.344
inhibitors and degraders does currently allow for

838
00:49:41.464 --> 00:49:45.204
sequencing for many years for most patients, with the caveat that

839
00:49:45.604 --> 00:49:48.224
many of these drugs are not yet available commercially.

840
00:49:48.984 --> 00:49:52.064
Fixed-duration approaches may further prolong drug sensitivity, allowing

841
00:49:52.124 --> 00:49:55.964
therapeutic options that may extend for many patients' natural lifespan.

842
00:49:56.644 --> 00:50:00.304
But I think continued work is necessary, especially to find effective strategies

843
00:50:00.314 --> 00:50:04.264
for high-risk patients where these timelines are probably not accurate, as well

844
00:50:04.284 --> 00:50:07.984
as for younger patients, where a 13- to 15-year approach is really not going to be

845
00:50:08.024 --> 00:50:08.624
good enough.

846
00:50:15.764 --> 00:50:19.714
So with that, I will end. And for the work done at Ohio State, I'd

847
00:50:19.724 --> 00:50:23.224
like to acknowledge our CLL clinical and research team, as well as the

848
00:50:23.244 --> 00:50:26.904
Experimental Hematology Laboratory, our collaborators,

849
00:50:27.124 --> 00:50:30.904
and our funding sources. And I'd be happy to take any questions.

850
00:50:37.464 --> 00:50:41.314
Thank you so much, Jen. Does anyone have a

851
00:50:41.314 --> 00:50:42.644
question at this time?

852
00:50:42.704 --> 00:50:43.924
Thank you for the excellent talk.

853
00:50:44.924 --> 00:50:48.824
I was wondering, you talked about how a mutation upon

854
00:50:48.864 --> 00:50:52.444
exposure to BTK inhibitors turns

855
00:50:52.524 --> 00:50:54.564
the nature of

856
00:50:56.024 --> 00:50:59.084
inhibition from reversible to irreversible.

857
00:51:00.204 --> 00:51:03.904
If you could elaborate on how does the

858
00:51:04.064 --> 00:51:07.764
structure of the receptor change to cause

859
00:51:07.824 --> 00:51:09.744
that kinetic change?

860
00:51:10.784 --> 00:51:11.504
Yeah. I

861
00:51:12.804 --> 00:51:16.644
don't know that I can fully explain how the structure of the receptor changes,

862
00:51:16.724 --> 00:51:20.164
but it appears that that mutation just inhibits or

863
00:51:20.524 --> 00:51:23.044
changes the binding kinetics such that,

864
00:51:24.364 --> 00:51:28.304
well, obviously instead of being irreversible, it's reversible, but the binding

865
00:51:28.324 --> 00:51:32.284
affinity is lower. And even the idea of the reversible binding there is

866
00:51:32.324 --> 00:51:35.924
relatively short, so all of the covalent inhibitors have very short

867
00:51:36.004 --> 00:51:39.624
half-lives, so when you change it to a reversible inhibitor, it's clinically not

868
00:51:39.644 --> 00:51:40.404
going to work anymore.

869
00:51:41.204 --> 00:51:44.924
Understood. And another question about this

870
00:51:46.244 --> 00:51:49.604
idea about only treating patients with a

871
00:51:49.944 --> 00:51:50.984
fixed duration.

872
00:51:52.324 --> 00:51:55.984
How do you think physicians and even patients can grapple with the

873
00:51:56.044 --> 00:51:57.034
idea that

874
00:51:58.604 --> 00:52:02.584
even if the disease has not completely entered into remission

875
00:52:02.744 --> 00:52:06.153
stage, you just stop the treatment because that's the

876
00:52:06.204 --> 00:52:10.064
paradigm, and then you start once again to reduce the

877
00:52:10.124 --> 00:52:12.544
probability of resistance? Are we risking

878
00:52:13.724 --> 00:52:17.424
the possibility of the disease itself taking over rather

879
00:52:17.524 --> 00:52:21.064
than it coming back due to

880
00:52:21.084 --> 00:52:21.644
resistance?

881
00:52:22.184 --> 00:52:24.044
Yeah. Actually, that's a really important question.

882
00:52:24.904 --> 00:52:28.604
And I should mention that the response rates to the fixed-duration

883
00:52:28.644 --> 00:52:32.604
regimens are upwards of 90% in the frontline setting.

884
00:52:32.684 --> 00:52:35.924
So pretty much every patient who you're going to be

885
00:52:35.964 --> 00:52:39.524
considering stopping at the end of therapy, they will be in a remission.

886
00:52:39.924 --> 00:52:42.504
And actually, even with these types of

887
00:52:43.904 --> 00:52:47.784
therapies, especially with triplets, but probably with some

888
00:52:47.844 --> 00:52:51.584
of the doublets too, we're getting undetectable minimal residual

889
00:52:51.644 --> 00:52:52.164
disease

890
00:52:52.984 --> 00:52:55.024
rates of upwards of 50%.

891
00:52:56.044 --> 00:52:59.764
And we see that the presence of minimal residual disease

892
00:52:59.864 --> 00:53:02.364
in IGHV unmutated CLL, so the more

893
00:53:03.324 --> 00:53:06.884
kind of activated group, the higher-risk group, that tracks with

894
00:53:06.954 --> 00:53:10.924
PFS. So the presence of MRD at the end of treatment for

895
00:53:11.004 --> 00:53:12.924
an unmutated IGHV patient

896
00:53:14.264 --> 00:53:18.204
is predictive of outcome. However, in the patients who have mutated IGHV,

897
00:53:18.324 --> 00:53:21.924
so the lower-risk group, we actually see lower rates of undetectable

898
00:53:22.004 --> 00:53:25.904
MRD in general. But it doesn't seem to matter, at least with

899
00:53:25.944 --> 00:53:28.084
the data that we have, it doesn't matter whether they

900
00:53:29.244 --> 00:53:29.844
have

901
00:53:30.764 --> 00:53:32.763
measurable disease at the end of therapy or not.

902
00:53:32.864 --> 00:53:35.744
Their remissions seem to be about the same and are very long.

903
00:53:36.264 --> 00:53:39.704
So I think to your point, I would not

904
00:53:39.904 --> 00:53:43.344
advocate treating a patient with a fixed-duration regimen and

905
00:53:43.464 --> 00:53:46.374
stopping when they still have a kind of gross disease.

906
00:53:46.774 --> 00:53:50.214
And there are a lot of studies looking at risk-adapted,

907
00:53:50.344 --> 00:53:54.044
response-adapted, or MRD-adapted approaches, where you would continue

908
00:53:54.144 --> 00:53:56.444
treatment until you get the deepest remission possible.

909
00:53:57.164 --> 00:53:57.604
Thank you.

910
00:54:02.044 --> 00:54:04.764
I think the resistance of BTK inhibitors,

911
00:54:04.964 --> 00:54:07.224
the

912
00:54:08.144 --> 00:54:09.884
reason is the continuous treatment, right?

913
00:54:09.984 --> 00:54:13.544
If you have fixed-duration treatment, you would induce less resistant

914
00:54:13.604 --> 00:54:17.424
mechanism, but continuous treatment ultimately will lead to

915
00:54:17.484 --> 00:54:18.564
some kind of resistance.

916
00:54:20.244 --> 00:54:23.044
So my question is, I don't fully understand the

917
00:54:23.724 --> 00:54:26.664
philosophy or the rationale to develop something like

918
00:54:27.584 --> 00:54:31.324
covalent and reversible,

919
00:54:31.384 --> 00:54:34.644
irreversible in one molecule. To me,

920
00:54:35.084 --> 00:54:37.024
first of all, it's relative, right?

921
00:54:37.204 --> 00:54:40.724
It's only so-called reversible or non-reversible on

922
00:54:40.824 --> 00:54:44.624
certain residues, not across the entire BTK,

923
00:54:44.844 --> 00:54:48.504
right? So there will be ultimately resistant

924
00:54:48.544 --> 00:54:50.444
mechanisms come out anyway.

925
00:54:51.304 --> 00:54:55.004
So I think to develop a new molecule with that kind of

926
00:54:55.064 --> 00:54:58.760
feature, does that really help? Or shall we just sequence the-...

927
00:54:58.780 --> 00:55:01.420
reversible after the irreversible.

928
00:55:01.780 --> 00:55:05.580
That will actually give you longer PFS instead of just a molecule has

929
00:55:05.600 --> 00:55:09.380
both mechanism, but maybe they will induce some kind of

930
00:55:09.940 --> 00:55:10.940
resistant mechanism

931
00:55:11.940 --> 00:55:15.460
which all the existing BTK is not going to work quicker.

932
00:55:15.780 --> 00:55:19.770
So I just don't know whether that's a smart way to do.

933
00:55:20.340 --> 00:55:22.240
Well, I think that's really an open question, right?

934
00:55:22.400 --> 00:55:26.350
So we don't know whether sequencing of those

935
00:55:26.360 --> 00:55:30.260
drugs is going to be better than even if-- what if you were to give a covalent

936
00:55:30.280 --> 00:55:32.420
and a non-covalent BTK inhibitor at the same time?

937
00:55:32.580 --> 00:55:36.000
So let's say you treat it with acalabrutinib plus piratubrutinib, we have no idea

938
00:55:36.060 --> 00:55:39.200
whether that would induce a longer remission than if you use the two drugs in

939
00:55:39.240 --> 00:55:43.140
sequence. I mean, similar to giving acalabrutinib plus

940
00:55:43.200 --> 00:55:45.300
venetoclax versus sequencing those drugs.

941
00:55:45.340 --> 00:55:49.320
So I think that the idea that you would definitely

942
00:55:49.360 --> 00:55:52.440
have a shorter remission with a dual approach is

943
00:55:52.960 --> 00:55:53.600
unknown.

944
00:55:54.440 --> 00:55:58.040
I think the pros of that approach would be like I said,

945
00:55:58.300 --> 00:56:02.260
treating it or using it in a resistant setting already where we know

946
00:56:02.300 --> 00:56:05.299
that some of the cells don't harbor

947
00:56:06.380 --> 00:56:10.360
the C481S mutation, for example. So even if in a patient who

948
00:56:10.460 --> 00:56:14.360
has disease resistant to piratubrutinib and a covalent BTK inhibitor,

949
00:56:14.980 --> 00:56:18.340
the cells are not all the same, and they don't all have one resistance mechanism.

950
00:56:18.400 --> 00:56:22.000
So a drug like that may be able to affect two types of cells

951
00:56:22.020 --> 00:56:22.470
differently.

952
00:56:24.680 --> 00:56:25.510
Can I ask another question?

953
00:56:27.440 --> 00:56:31.020
Do you recall that whether the BTK degraders

954
00:56:31.980 --> 00:56:32.720
people are developing,

955
00:56:34.440 --> 00:56:37.290
can they overcome the PLC gamma 2

956
00:56:37.290 --> 00:56:40.720
resistance, I mean, tissues?

957
00:56:41.100 --> 00:56:41.110
Mm-hmm.

958
00:56:41.580 --> 00:56:43.820
And if that's a yes, why?

959
00:56:43.880 --> 00:56:44.540
Yeah.

960
00:56:45.560 --> 00:56:47.900
So as to the why, I don't know exactly.

961
00:56:48.020 --> 00:56:50.960
Actually, I have a grad student in the lab who's trying to look at that right now.

962
00:56:51.860 --> 00:56:55.820
But it probably has to do with the fact that though we think about the BCR pathway

963
00:56:55.900 --> 00:56:59.680
as linear, it's not actually linear, and there are ways that you can go

964
00:56:59.760 --> 00:57:00.800
around BTK.

965
00:57:02.640 --> 00:57:06.240
Whether they work, I think that the answer is probably yes,

966
00:57:06.440 --> 00:57:09.659
although we don't really have that long of

967
00:57:10.840 --> 00:57:14.660
follow-up, and we don't have that much resistance data available.

968
00:57:15.740 --> 00:57:19.240
And one way that they might not work would be that

969
00:57:19.620 --> 00:57:23.400
many times these mutations are at low allelic frequency, so it does take some time

970
00:57:23.440 --> 00:57:26.180
for them to grow out. So I think yes, but I don't know.

971
00:57:28.240 --> 00:57:32.220
Can I just ask a clinical question to close this part of

972
00:57:32.300 --> 00:57:32.920
the session?

973
00:57:33.960 --> 00:57:37.360
In CML, we would naturally sequence

974
00:57:37.860 --> 00:57:39.840
the patient before we change therapy.

975
00:57:40.140 --> 00:57:43.600
Is that something that we should be doing now with CLL?

976
00:57:44.060 --> 00:57:44.720
And if so,

977
00:57:45.780 --> 00:57:48.880
are we asking for a targeted panel, or how are we doing it?

978
00:57:49.280 --> 00:57:51.920
Yep, so great question. The answer is absolutely yes.

979
00:57:52.000 --> 00:57:55.740
We should be sequencing patients every time they relapse on therapy, whether it's a

980
00:57:55.780 --> 00:57:58.140
continuous or a fixed-duration therapy.

981
00:57:58.860 --> 00:58:02.320
There's actually a lot of commercial panels available, and now they pretty much all

982
00:58:02.360 --> 00:58:05.280
include BTK and PLC gamma 2.

983
00:58:06.200 --> 00:58:09.520
We have an institutional one we use as well as many other places do that also

984
00:58:09.540 --> 00:58:12.380
